The triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, together they have 29 percent
The noticeable weakening of the two sides of the previous grand coalition and the significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties have led to early parliamentary elections in Austria on Sunday, according to preliminary results.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly heavy losses, with the position of current President Wilhelm Molterter seriously shaken.
On the contrary, the election leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the Coroan hechtman Jörg Haider is preparing a triumphant return to national politics.
According to preliminary results, the Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) remains the strongest party in the country with 29.8 percent of the vote, but it has lost 5.5 percent of the vote since the last elections in 2006.
Even worse, the ÖVP is losing almost nine percent of the vote, at 25.6 percent.
It is the worst result for both of these major parties in Austria's postwar history and especially for the populists who called an early election, a literally disastrous result.
Even at the beginning of July, when the ÖVP withdrew from the coalition, the populists had a significant lead in preferences over the SPÖ.
But the voters have clearly punished them for letting the government fail.
The first reactions to the results were speculation about the possible resignation of the party chairman and former vice chancellor Wilhelm Molterterer.
Observers believe that this could happen as early as Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party presidency.
Such a development would likely pave the way for the increasingly likely outcome of the election, namely the renewal of a grand coalition between the SPÖ and the ÖVP.
However, given the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Free Party (FPÖ) gained 18 percent of the vote and the BZÖ 11 percent - the Social Democrats also expressed concern about a repeat of 1999, when the populists agreed with the populists (the FPÖ was still united, but split from the BZÖ in 2005) on a joint government that even triggered sanctions from the European Union.
This is clearly the development Haider is betting on, as he has already said he is ready to work with any party and envisages returning to Vienna to national politics.
The Greens also entered the parliament, but lost easily and fell from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
None of the other parties clearly crossed the four percent threshold and made it into parliament.
