Turkish diplomatic horizons widen
Long before Turkey began to seek membership in the European Union, European powers were eager to penetrate deep into Turkey's territory.
On the eastern shore of the Bosphorus, perhaps just twenty steps into Asia, stands one of the finest monuments to this failed imperial ambition.
Hydarpasa railway station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in a neo-Renaissance style.
Well, that's what the tour guide will tell you.
The building sits circularly at the end of the platforms with towers at each corner of the façade, looking indistinguishable from some provincial German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slowly falling apart.
But once one enters the vaulted vault, one can no longer doubt the size of the enterprise whose westernmost gate was the station.
The station was opened in August 1908 by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, which was a late entrant into the game of empires, intended to realize its ambitions for domination of the Middle East with this railway, which would lead to Damascus, Baghdad and beyond into what is now Saudi Arabia.
But German imperial ambitions collapsed during World War I.
Their tracks were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular troops.
The relative isolation from surrounding territory, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
British and colonial troops were advancing from Egypt, driving the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And bad news for Hydarpasa station too.
In 1917, an explosion on an ammunition train destroyed its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has been steadily declining and history has bypassed it.
Today, however, this gateway to Anatolia and further east serves - at least symbolically - to highlight the expanding horizons of Turkish diplomacy.
The ruling Justice and Development Party (AKP) has created a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding territory, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
Now a new policy is in place - Turkey is getting involved.
It is remarkable that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To examine the parameters of this new policy, I took a night train to Ankara, the Turkish capital, where I was to meet with one of the AKP's leading experts on foreign policy, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a curvy ride on the tracks that resembled the Old World rhythms of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital, designed as a new city for a secular state that wants to turn its back on its Ottoman past.
But the AKP, with its well-known Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in Turkish consensus.
It has aroused suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
The taxi took me to the AKP headquarters, a state-of-the-art stone and metal building purposefully built in a developing suburb, surrounded by half-built department stores and department stores, where middle managers in business suits - men and women - meet to make early morning deals.
Suat Kiniklioglu could easily be a centre-right politician from almost any other European political party.
Jacket, tie, I'm sure he had a Blackberry.
"The party's foreign policy aims to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate neighbourhood.
The Cold War was an anomaly", he told me.
Turkey was cut off from its perimeter.
Today, he has to look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't a choice.
It had to do both.
"But there will surely come a time", I asked, "when Turkey may have to decide?"
"Turkey", he said, "did not wish to have to make such a decision".
He then stressed what almost everyone I spoke to here has said almost by heart: Turkey's relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the Black Sea region are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, it seems that Europe as a whole can, metaphorically speaking, go east on these tracks to Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha station, after another mostly sleepless night, I thought of those two German gentlemen, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who watched this building being built a hundred years ago.
How surprised they would be to find that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East may now be, in large part, in Turkish hands.
And as I waited in the harbor for the ferry back across the Bosporus, I remembered that in those days Turkey was called "the sick man of Europe".
So it seems that at least back then, there was little doubt as to which continent should claim this fascinating land.
