The "Car Bee" prevents collisions
To advance the development of accident protection technology, Nissan has taken inspiration from nature, specifically bees.
This Japanese company has developed a robot that mimics the flight of bees to prevent collisions.
One of these is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which represents the first step in collision avoidance technology.
Engineers at the Nissan Motor Co. Center for Technical Advancement have developed the robot in collaboration with the Center for Advancement in Scientific and Technological Research at Japan's prestigious University of Tokyo.
According to Kazuhiro Doie, general manager of public relations for technology, research and development of the brand, the BR23C is presented as an extension of the four zones of Nissan's safety shield.
The robot's mission is to enhance the collision prevention capabilities of this brand of vehicles.
During flight, each bee creates its own personal oval-shaped space, which closely resembles a Nissan safety shield.
Most important, however, are the bee's complex eyes, which are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, allowing the bee to fly in its personal space without stopping.
In creating this visual feature, engineers designed what they called a laser rangefinder.
It detects obstacles up to two metres in a 180-degree radius in front of BR23C, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts it to a collision warning.
"The moment an obstacle is detected, the robot mimics the bee's movements and instantly changes direction by turning the wheels at right angles or even higher to avoid a collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is the fact that all the maneuvers are completely instinctive.
If it were not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobile Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, a robot cannot move up and down or diagonally, but is limited to two dimensions and the direction it can move in by rotating its wheels, not in an infinite number of directions and possibilities as a bee.
So in addition to accelerating and decelerating, Nissan used the rotation function to prevent the robot from colliding.
"The machine only needs to process information every few seconds and act on that information.
It requires no storage of information or logical intuition from previous maneuvers, allowing it to operate without interruption with only two dozen kilobytes of memory.
It may surprise you, but in memory we're not talking about gigabits or mega".
This is the first step in the development of new technologies for instant collision avoidance, technologies that Nissan predicts will be used in production cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible future use of this technology could be to incorporate a unit into a GPS satellite navigation system that would guide the driver to their destination while avoiding obstacles on the road.
