Morgan Stanley opens up its MUFG capital
Morgan Stanley Banking House announced that Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG), Japan's largest bank, is joining its ranks Wednesday, issuing $9 billion to raise 21 percent of its capital.
A week after disclosing their preliminary agreement, the two banks explained that MUFG intends to buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley common stock at a price of $25.25 per share, representing a total of $3 billion.
The price negotiated is 19% lower than the book value of the securities at 31 August.
MUFG Bank is investing an additional USD 6 billion in the acquisition of convertible securities, which will provide a 10% return and whose exchange rate is USD 31.25.
Morgan Stanley has specified that the entire operation will be conducted at an average unit price of $29, or 28% below its current exchange rate.
Morgan Stanley shares, however, were down 6.79% to $23.07 at around 5pm Greenwich time.
"This strategic merger represents an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley's transition to banking holding status", explained John Mack, CEO of the US group.
Morgan Stanley passed a new charter last week, which is supposed to allow it to diversify its operations, but also put it under the supervision of the Federal Reserve.
His merger with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing Wall Street's biggest ace to take a far more cautious approach than before.
The terms unveiled on Monday among other things show that the deal has been altered over the past few days: last Monday, Morgan only announced that he would sell up to 20% of his shares to the Japanese for about $8.5 billion.
"A week ago", explained Toshihide Mizuno, MUFG's executive director in Tokyo, "we thought our participation would be purely routine.
However, given the current economic and market situation, we wanted to minimise risks and also hedge ourselves.'
On the basis of the weighted average price, MUFG will pay 7% less for Morgan Stanley securities than their book value.
