Fox in the henhouse
Life and health insurance companies in America often reject the possibility of contracting with a drug buyer based on the information people have about their purchases.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection program that requires that the use of prescription drug data is always subject to the consent of the person concerned.
It has to be in the hands of an independent person, or we're leaving the chicken coop to the fox", quotes the Washington Post as saying of Richard Dick, author of a program designed to monitor prescriptions.
Insurance companies make premiums and sums paid in the event of insurance events dependent on the health of the claimants and, if the risk is assessed as too great, they do not even take out insurance with them.
Previously, they sent the persons concerned for medical examinations and only concluded the contract after knowing the results.
A decade ago, Dick devised a much cheaper method: a pharmacy customer could easily see what medications he had bought in the last year and a half from an ID number, from which the program could infer what his illness was and what his health was.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol-lowering drugs, this indicates that he has practically uncontrollably high blood fats, which immediately places him in a higher risk category.
There are several versions of the program, some of which also determine the risk factor, so that the insurance company has little to do but paperwork, although there are some minor difficulties.
The disadvantages include that some drugs can be used for several purposes, such as for migraines and hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
These are a significant risk-increasing factor for commercial insurers, whereas the first difficulties are not.
Special companies have been set up to collect and process data and ask the patient's consent before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies.
Now they are being forced to do so by the authorities, even though they have not been punished for their negligence.
Some companies have recently begun to combine laboratory test results with data on medications used to provide even more accurate pictures of patients' health.
Data will be accessed by more and more companies, and at the same time, it will become increasingly difficult to control their use.
There is a special law on the protection of health data, but its effect is limited to healthcare providers and insurance companies.
A bill that would give the federal government the power to control companies that specialize in providing data is before Congress.
Richard Dick recognises that this is not enough: he has therefore developed his programme to make the transfer of data subject explicitly consented to.
Another thing is that he can hardly refuse the permission in question, otherwise the insurance companies will not contract him.
So chickens are a little dependent on the fox's goodwill after all.
