Madera County Sheriff John Anderson dispelled any remaining doubts: "The plane has been found, we have sent a team there and we are now certain that it is exactly the one that Steve Fossett was flying on the day he disappeared", he told a news conference.
The sheriff's office has determined that no human remains were found on the plane or in the area.
The 63-year-old millionaire has been presumed dead since February.
The U.S. National Transportation Safety Board (NSB) announced that hours after the wreckage was identified, an investigation team was dispatched to identify the plane: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, missing since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington, Nevada, for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, near the Nevada border, some of Fossett's personal effects were found by a couple near their Mammoth Lakes residence.
There are two documents in Fossett's name, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a jacket.
The search for Fossett was called off a month after he disappeared.
